Wisconsin animal rescue takes in three eight-week-old baby bears after an older cub accidentally SUFFOCATED their mom to death while they were tranquilized by researchers in den

A Wisconsin wildlife rehab took in three eight-week-old bear cubs after their mother was killed in a research accident. Wild Instincts, an animal rehab center in Rhinelander, took in the tottering baby bears after their mother was suffocated in their den. An older, two-year-old 125-pound cub rolled onto her head while the bears were tranquilized during a routine replacement of the mama bear's radio collar. Mark Naniot, the director of Wild Instincts, said last week on Wisconsin Public Radio's 'The Morning Show' that he wasn't sure what the researchers were studying - regardless, he said, 'humans broke it, so we should fix it.' Researchers rushed to get the orphaned bears to the wildlife rehab within two and a half hours, Naniot said.  Now, they are just taking their first wobbly steps. They are being bottle fed and eating well, he said, and have doubled in size since early February. Baby bears are one of the most expensive animals cared for by the clinic, costing roughly $3,000 to $4,000 each for the eight or so months until they are around 100 pounds and can be released into the wild. Staffers at the clinic have been putting in 16 and 17 hour shifts seven days a week to cater to their around-the-clock needs while still caring for the other animals at the facility - 'we're cleaning toilets one minute and feeding bears the next minute. So, it's a situation where we have to basically do it all.'
